data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","sequence_number":527,"item_id":"msg_0b83f2d0a0094d870069177c2ea1b48194a2ea1a4df7bff584","output_index":1,"content_index":0,"text":"Do you mean a nuclear reactor that produces steam (for driving turbines), or something else? I’ll answer for the common meaning: a reactor that produces steam from heat released by a nuclear chain reaction.\n\nShort definition\n- A steam-producing (nuclear) reactor is a device where heat from nuclear fission is used to boil water or otherwise produce steam, which then drives turbines to generate electricity or provide process heat.\n\nHow it works (basic steps)\n1. Fuel assemblies in the reactor core undergo controlled fission and release heat.\n2. A coolant (usually water) removes heat from the core.\n3. Depending on the design, that heated water either:\n   - Boils inside the reactor vessel to produce steam (Boiling Water Reactor, BWR), or\n   - Transfers heat through a steam generator to a secondary loop where water turns to steam (Pressurized Water Reactor, PWR).\n4. The steam drives turbines connected to electrical generators.\n5. Steam is condensed back to water in a condenser and returned to the steam cycle.\n\nKey components\n- Reactor core (fuel, cladding)\n- Control rods (to control the fission rate)\n- Coolant/moderator (often water)\n- Pressure vessel or reactor vessel\n- Steam generator (in PWRs) or direct steam outlet (in BWRs)\n- Turbine, condenser, feedwater pump\n- Containment structure and safety systems\n\nMajor reactor types that produce steam\n- Boiling Water Reactor (BWR): steam is produced in the reactor vessel and goes directly to the turbine.\n- Pressurized Water Reactor (PWR): primary loop keeps water under high pressure so it doesn’t boil; heat is transferred to a secondary loop where steam is produced.\n- Other types (heavy-water reactors, some gas-cooled reactors) also produce steam though with different coolants or steam-generation arrangements.\n\nSafety and design features\n- Multiple physical barriers to contain radioactivity (fuel cladding, reactor vessel, containment building)\n- Control rods and automatic shutdown systems\n- Emergency core cooling systems and decay-heat removal systems\n- Redundant and diverse safety systems\n\nUses\n- Electricity generation (power plants)\n- Marine propulsion (nuclear submarines and aircraft carriers)\n- District heating, desalination, industrial process heat (in some designs)\n\nIf you meant a different kind of “steam reactor” (for example, a chemical steam reformer used to make hydrogen), tell me and I’ll explain that instead. Would you like more detail on BWR vs PWR, safety, or how a steam turbine cycle works?","logprobs":[]}

